#week-title("Four", "Finalising the Tyro Letter & Quarter III Preparation")

=== Core Teaching

The letter to a future Tyro, drafted in Year Three Month 7, is now finalised.
This is not a piece of inspirational writing for a general audience — it is
a specific, honest communication from someone who has completed three years of
alchemical study to someone who is about to begin.

*What makes the Tyro letter genuinely useful.* Most advice given by experienced
practitioners to beginners falls into one of two errors:
1. *Overemphasis on the difficulty:* warnings and caveats that intimidate
   without illuminating.
2. *Overemphasis on the reward:* descriptions of what becomes possible that
   bypass the realistic picture of what is actually required.

The Tyro letter that serves the future student avoids both. It is specific
rather than general, honest rather than inspiring, particular rather than
universal. It describes the actual experience of the work — what Year One Month
3 felt like, what the first calcination revealed, what the inner Nigredo was
in this practitioner's case — not the abstract teaching about these things.

The tradition's insistence that the experienced practitioner share honestly
rather than impressively is itself an expression of the Covenant: "Not to
diminish the Work by sensationalising it."

*Quarter III Gathering preparation.* The student assembles for sharing: a
complete account of all active mineral preparations; a reading from their
alchemical journal from across the three years; their declaration of ongoing
practice (still in draft); and the finalised Tyro letter.

=== Topics This Week

- What makes the Tyro letter genuinely useful: specific, honest, particular
- Avoiding both the intimidating and the inspiring error
- Finalising the letter for the Quarter III Gathering
- Preparing the full account of active preparations for sharing

